  <!-- Header Section -->
  <header class="header">
    <h1>CHM102 - Introductory Chemistry II</h1>
    <p>Explore the fundamental concepts of chemistry, including qualitative analysis, chemical bonding, and organic chemistry.</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <main class="course-container">
    <!-- Course Information -->
    <section class="course-info">
      <p><strong>Course Code:</strong> CHM 102</p>
      <p><strong>Course Title:</strong> Introductory Chemistry II</p>
      <p><strong>Credit Load:</strong> 3 + 1 + 0 (4 Units)</p>
      <p><strong>Semester:</strong> Second Semester</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Topics List Section -->
    <section class="topics-list" id="topics-section">
      <h2>Course Outline</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="qualitative-analysis">Qualitative Analysis (Inorganic)</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Tests for simple cations and anions.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="identification-organic-compounds">Identification of Organic Compounds</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Isolation and purification.</li>
            <li>Qualitative analysis: Tests for common elements (C, H, N, S, halogens, etc.).</li>
            <li>Quantitative analysis using Dumas, Kjeldahl's, and Carius methods.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="chemical-bonding">Chemical Bonding</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Why and how atoms combine?</li>
            <li>The molecule and chemical bonding; electrons in molecules.</li>
            <li>Ionic, covalent, dative and complex bonding; polarity of bonds.</li>
            <li>Co-ordinate bonds; metallic bonds; basic crystalline structure (e.g., NaCl) and metallic lattices.</li>
            <li>Hybridization and resonance in chemical bonding.</li>
            <li>Chemistry of Hydrogen, Noble Gases, Alkali Metals (Group I) and the Alkaline Earth Metals (Group II).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="intro-organic-chemistry">Introduction to Organic Chemistry</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Introduction to the term "Organic Chemistry."</li>
            <li>Hybridization in Carbon - sp3, sp2, and sp hybridization.</li>
            <li>Physical properties as related to structures - bond length, strength, rotation, etc.</li>
            <li>Electrophiles and Nucleophiles - Examples to include acids and bases.</li>
            <li>Homolytic and Heterolytic fission of bonds.</li>
            <li>Factors influencing organic reactions - inductive and mesomeric effects, steric factors, etc.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="organic-chemistry">Organic Chemistry</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Homologous series and Functional groups' chemistry.</li>
            <li>Types of Organic reactions.</li>
            <li>Isomerism - Structural, Geometric and Optical Isomers.</li>
            <li>Chemistry of Hydrocarbons (alkanes, alkenes, alkynes, alkyl halides and Grignard reagents):
              <ul>
                <li>Nomenclature (IUPAC rules to be treated under Alkanes).</li>
                <li>Preparation.</li>
                <li>Physical properties.</li>
                <li>Chemical reactions with simple mechanisms where applicable.</li>
                <li>Applications.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="main-group-chemistry-iii-v">Main Group Chemistry (Groups III - V)</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Trends in properties of elements (structures, ionization energy, physical and chemical properties).</li>
            <li>Properties of selected types of compounds - hydrides, oxides, acids, and bases.</li>
            <li>Chemistry of B and Al; C and Pb; N and Bi.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="main-group-chemistry-vi-vii-transition-metals">Main Group Chemistry (Groups VI and VII) and Transition Metal Chemistry</a>
          <ul>
            <li>MAIN GROUP CHEMISTRY (Groups VI and VII):
              <ul>
                <li>Trend in properties of elements.</li>
                <li>Properties of selected types of compounds.</li>
                <li>Chemistry of O and S; F and Cl.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>TRANSITION SERIES:
              <ul>
                <li>Properties of elements and compounds of d-block elements, lanthanides, and actinides.</li>
                <li>Electronic configuration; Complexes and IUPAC nomenclature of complexes.</li>
                <li>Chemistry of Cr, Fe, Co, Ni and Cu; particularly of the most common oxidation states.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="alcohols-ethers-aldehydes-ketones">Chemistry of Alcohols, Ethers, Aldehydes and Ketones; Carboxylic Acids, Derivatives and Amines</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Nomenclature (IUPAC).</li>
            <li>Preparation, Structure, Physical properties and general reactions.</li>
            <li>Introduction to Aromatic compounds.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#" class="topic-link" data-topic="carbohydrates-proteins-lipids">Carbohydrates, Proteins and Lipids</a>
          <ul>
            <li>Simple treatment of carbohydrates - monosaccharides (e.g. glucose and fructose), disaccharides, and polysaccharides.</li>
            <li>Proteins - amino acids, peptide bonds etc.</li>
            <li>Lipids - Fats and Oils, Soap and Detergent.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

